{
  "id": "celery_celery_10298",
  "repo_name": "celery/celery",
  "repo_url": "https://github.com/celery/celery",
  "base_commit": "8540c0881df2545a75d91952b45c1845d4c8eab4",
  "pr_number": 10298,
  "issue_number": 10294,
  "issue_title": "celery 5.6.3 regression: _reconnect_pubsub breaks with redis-py < 5.3.0",
  "issue_body": "## Checklist\n\n- [x] I have checked the [issues list](https://github.com/celery/celery/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3A%22Issue+Type%3A+Bug+Report%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22+)\n  for similar or identical bug reports.\n- [x] I have checked the [pull requests list](https://github.com/celery/celery/pulls?q=is%3Apr+label%3A%22PR+Type%3A+Bugfix%22+-label%3A%22Category%3A+Documentation%22+)\n  for existing proposed fixes.\n- [x] I have checked the [commit log](https://github.com/celery/celery/commits/main)\n  to find out if the bug was already fixed in the main branch.\n- [x] I have included all related issues and possible duplicate issues\n  in this issue (If there are none, check this box anyway).\n\n## Mandatory Debugging Information\n\n- **Celery version**: 5.6.3\n- **kombu version**: 5.6.2\n- **redis-py version**: 4.6.0\n- **Python version**: 3.11\n- **OS**: Linux (Debian)\n\n## Related Issues and Possible Duplicates\n\n- #9769 \u2014 the original deprecation warning report. PR #10036 (which fixed #9769) was milestoned for 5.7.0 but was included in the 5.6.3 release without a corresponding bump to the minimum redis-py version.\n- celery/kombu#2511 \u2014 bumps kombu's redis-py minimum to >=5.3.0 to match, but is milestoned for kombu 5.7.0 and has not shipped.\n\n## Description\n\nCelery 5.6.3 introduced a regression that breaks the Redis result backend's pubsub reconnection path for anyone using redis-py < 5.3.0.\n\nPR #10036 removed the positional arguments from the `get_connection()` call in `_reconnect_pubsub`:\n\n**v5.6.2** ([redis.py#L120](https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/v5.6.2/celery/backends/redis.py#L120)):\n```python\nself._pubsub.connection = self._pubsub.connection_pool.get_connection(\n    'pubsub', self._pubsub.shard_hint\n)\n```\n\n**v5.6.3** ([redis.py#L114](https://github.com/celery/celery/blob/v5.6.3/celery/backends/redis.py#L114)):\n```python\nself._pubsub.connection = self._pubsub.connection_pool.get_connection()\n```\n\nIn redis-py < 5.3.0, `ConnectionPool.get_connection(command_name, *keys, **options)` requires `command_name` as a positional argument ([redis-py v4.6.0 connection.py#L1449](https://github.com/redis/redis-py/blob/v4.6.0/redis/connection.py#L1449)). The no-arg call raises:\n\n```\nTypeError: ConnectionPool.get_connection() missing 1 required positional argument: 'command_name'\n```\n\nThis only surfaces when a Redis pubsub connection drops (TLS keepalive timeout, idle disconnect, infrastructure cycling) and Celery attempts to reconnect. The initial connection works fine, making the bug intermittent and difficult to diagnose.\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n\n1. Install `celery==5.6.3` with `redis==4.6.0` (or any redis-py < 5.3.0)\n2. Configure a Redis result backend\n3. Start a Celery worker and submit a task that returns a result\n4. Force a Redis pubsub disconnect (e.g., kill the TCP connection, wait for idle timeout, or restart the Redis server)\n5. Celery's `_reconnect_pubsub` fires and raises `TypeError`\n\n## Expected Behavior\n\nThe pubsub connection should reconnect transparently, as it did in celery 5.6.2.\n\n## Actual Behavior\n\n```\nTypeError: ConnectionPool.get_connection() missing 1 required positional argument: 'command_name'\n```\n\nThe reconnection fails, and any pending result consumers break.\n\n## Root Cause\n\nPR #10036 was milestoned for 5.7.0 (where presumably redis-py >= 5.3.0 would be required), but it was included in the 5.6.3 release. Celery 5.6.x does not require redis-py >= 5.3.0, so the `get_connection()` call without arguments is a breaking change for existing users on redis-py 4.x.\n\nThis is a semver violation \u2014 a patch release (5.6.2 \u2192 5.6.3) broke a public API contract.\n\n## Suggested Fix\n\nEither:\n\n1. **Patch release (5.6.4)**: Revert the `get_connection()` change to restore the positional args, preserving compatibility with redis-py 4.x. Or conditionally pass the args based on the redis-py version.\n2. **Minimum version bump**: Add `redis>=5.3.0` to celery's dependencies in the 5.6.x line (though this is itself a breaking change for a patch release).\n\nOption 1 seems like the correct path for a patch release.",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-09T05:16:01Z",
